[[ja:海人部]]

'''Amabe''' (海人部 or 海部) were occupational groups ({{ill|Shinabe clans|en|Shinabe clans|qid=Q11418456|lt=Shinabe|1=Shinabe clans}}) in Japan before the {{ill|Taika Reform|en|Taika Reform|qid=Q570140|lt=Taika Reform|1=Taika Reform}}, living along the coast and contributing marine products to the central government.

They are not to be confused with the {{ill|Ama People|qid=Q9495537}} or with the {{ill|Amabe clan|en|Amabe clan|qid=Q65272445|lt=Amabe clan}} which runs [[Kono Shrine]]

== Overview ==
The term "{{ill|Ama (diving)|en|Ama (diving)|qid=Q1577970|lt=Ama diver|1=Ama (diving)}}" (あま), also written as "海," "海士," or "白水郎," referred to fishermen and coastal inhabitants skilled in fishing and navigation. They likely served the court by supplying marine products and utilizing their exceptional maritime skills. They also played significant roles in interactions with the continent and the Korean Peninsula and, according to folklore, may have been associated with performing arts.
The Amabe were distributed west of {{ill|Tōtōmi Province|en|Tōtōmi Province|qid=Q1048864|lt=Tōtōmi Province|1=Tōtōmi Province}}, {{ill|Shinano Province|en|Shinano Province|qid=Q289250|lt=Shinano Province|1=Shinano Province}}, and {{ill|Echizen Province|en|Echizen Province|qid=Q1047144|lt=Echizen Province|1=Echizen Province}}, with notable clusters in {{ill|Kii Province|en|Kii Province|qid=Q864053|lt=Kii Province|1=Kii Province}}, {{ill|Awaji Province|en|Awaji Province|qid=Q1053717|lt=Awaji Province|1=Awaji Province}}, {{ill|Awa Province (Tokushima)|en|Awa Province (Tokushima)|qid=Q907457|lt=Awa Province (Tokushima)|1=Awa Province (Tokushima)}}, and {{ill|Kibi Province|en|Kibi Province|qid=Q1155128|lt=Kibi Province|1=Kingdom of Kibi}}. Local Amabe were led by titles such as Amabe no Atai (海部直), Amabe no Obito (海部首), or Amabe no Kimi (海部公). The leaders, including the Amabe no Atai, were subordinate to {{ill|Tomonomiyatsuko|ja|伴造|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomonomiyatsuko|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} clans like the {{ill|Owari clan|en|Owari clan|qid=Q11465311|lt=Owari clan|1=Owari clan}} and {{ill|Kibi clan|en|Kibi clan|qid=Q11412645|lt=Kibi clan|1=Kibi clan}}. Titles such as Atai, Obito, and Kimi likely derived from the Ranks of their supervising Tomonomiyatsuko.<ref name="#1">{{Cite book|title=日本書紀研究 第二十四巻|author=上遠野浩一|publisher=塙書房|year=2002|qq=}}</ref>
== Azumi Clan and Amabe ==
The {{ill|Azumi clan|ja|安曇氏|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azumi clan|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 阿曇氏|1=Azumi people|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q3377806}} is noted in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|qid=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}} (entry for the 11th month of Emperor {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|en|Emperor Ōjin|qid=Q317997|lt=Ōjin|1=Emperor Ōjin}}'s 3rd year): 
{{quotation|The Ama in various places defied orders. Azumi no Muraji Ōhama Sukuneno was sent to pacify them and was appointed Governor of the Ama.|source=Nihon Shoki|qq=}}
Additionally, the 8th-month entry for the 5th year of Emperor Ōjin states, "Governments established Amabe and Yamamori-no-Be in various provinces," indicating the origin of the Amabe. The Azumi clan's role as the overseers of the Ama likely began around this time, though their actual function as Ama leaders is documented during the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|en|Empress Suiko|qid=Q298057|lt=Empress Suiko|1=Empress Suiko}}.
The surnames of Amabe varied regionally—{{ill|Atai (kabane)|ja|直|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Atai (kabane)|1=Q11581705|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11581705}}, {{ill|Muraji|en|Muraji|qid=Q2735611|lt=Muraji|1=Muraji}}, and {{ill|Omi (title)|en|Omi (title)|qid=Q2574718|lt=Omi (kabane)|1=Omi (title)}}—reflecting the clans that integrated them (e.g., Owari and Kibi clans). Some Amabe allied with the Azumi, while others aligned with different clans. This suggests the Amabe were established across Japan independently of the Azumi, integrating into the Yamato government without direct ties to the Azumi clan in all cases.<ref name="#1"/>
== Historical Records ==
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|qid=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}}, during the reign of Emperor Ōjin:
{{quotation|In this era, the Amabe, {{ill|Radical 46|en|Radical 46|qid=Q99671|lt=Yamabe|1=Radical 46}}, Yamamoribe, and Isebe were established.|source=Kojiki|qq=}}
The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}} (Volume 10) elaborates:
{{quotation|The Ama in various places defied orders. Azumi no Muraji Ōhama Sukuneno was sent to pacify them and was appointed Governor of the Ama.|source=Nihon Shoki, Emperor Ōjin, 3rd year, 11th month|qq=draft}}
This period coincides with the late 4th century, a time of Yamato expansion into the Korean Peninsula, necessitating the organization of maritime forces.
== Notes on Tattoos and Ama Culture ==
The {{ill|Wajinden|en|Wajinden|qid=Q1135798|lt=Weizhi Worenchuan|1=Wajinden}} mentions:
{{quotation|Men, regardless of age, have tattooed faces and bodies. This tradition, derived from ancient Chinese practices, was believed to protect against sea creatures. Over time, it evolved into a decorative custom, varying by region.|source=Wei Zhi|qq=}}
These traditions suggest a connection between Ama customs and tattooing practices noted in historical records.
